                {{ elements.csTitle('h2', 'Overview') }}
                <div class="cs:content">
                    <p>
                        Abstract paved the way for multi-designer collaboration in <span class="space:nowrap">UI design</span> tools with their initial product that provided version control for Sketch files. Post-Figma, and multiplayer design, Abstract was left searching for what's next. The solution that Abstract arrived at was a product called Notebooks, a very similar product to Notion, eventually acquired by Adobe.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <figure class="cs:figure">
                <div class="relative w:100p flex flex:col radius:md overflow:hidden border:1 border:edge-1 max-w:672">
                    {{ elements.csBrowserNav('www.abstact.com')}}
                    <img src="/assets/images/photos/abstract/mike-stilling-abstract-notebooks-home.webp" width="1152" height="1400" class="mb:n1 max-w:100p flex-shrink:0" style="border-radius:0;" alt="The hero section of the redesigned Abstract marketing site homepage featuring large text, small conversation blurbs, and a sneak peak of the product UI">
                </div>
                <figcaption>
                    The redesigned hero area <span class="space:nowrap">of Abstract's marketing website by Mike</span>
                </figcaption>
            </figure>

            <div data-toc-linked id="duties" class="cs:chunk">
                {{ elements.csTitle('h3', 'Duties') }}
                <div class="cs:content">
                    <p>
                        With the design tools space changing at the speed of light, Mike had to build fast and together, with his teammates in marketing, to rapidly transform a company known for it's initial product into something new. Both Abstract <span class="italic color:ink-1">(initial product)</span> and Notebooks were being sold to design teams, which meant Mike had to hit an extremely high-level of creativity and craft in the work that he was creating to impress the audience.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Mike worked directly on Abstract's marketing website, product, and brand. As a small marketing/brand design team, it was important to wear more than just one hat. Mike worked cross-functionally with the marketing, product, sales, and customer success org to gain a deep understanding of the challenges that customers were facing. This understanding ensured that the work Mike was creating aligned with both customer needs as well as company north stars.
                    </p>
                    <figure class="cs:figure pt:40 pb:48 sm:pb:56 sm:pt:64">
                        <div class="relative w:100p flex flex:col radius:md overflow:hidden border:1 border:edge-1">
                            {{ elements.csBrowserNav('www.inthemargin.com')}}
                            <img src="/assets/images/photos/abstract/mike-stilling-abstract-in-the-margin-home.webp" width="1152" height="820" class="mb:n1 max-w:100p flex-shrink:0" style="border-radius:0;" alt="The landing page of In The Margin, a Tumblr inspired website Mike built for Abstract as a content hub">
                        </div>
                        <figcaption>
                            In the Margin, a Tumblr inspired content hub <span class="space:nowrap">Mike designed/built for Abstract</span>
                        </figcaption>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        Naturally, Abstract had a very thoughtful design process. Mike would present work at least once, if not twice, a week to the greater design team as well as other stakeholders. Much of the work and thought behind the work was being asynchronously contained and shared within Notebooks <span class="italic color:ink-1">(the new product)</span>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Tool-wise, Abstract's initial site was built in Webflow, so Mike continued building within that. When designing for brand and product, Mike worked in Figma and prototyped in AfterEffects using AEUX to port designs between the tools.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <figure class="cs:figure">
                <img src="/assets/images/photos/abstract/mike-stilling-abstract-blog-graphic.webp" width="1104" height="687" class="border:1 border:edge-1" alt="A blog graphic with simplified UI components on a forest green background that Mike created for Abstract">
